    "markdown": "## MRI Shoulder without Contrast Overview\n\n### What is MRI Shoulder Without Contrast?\nAn \\*\\*MRI shoulder without contrast\\*\\* is a magnetic-resonance imaging test that maps the soft tissues and bones of your shoulder using powerful magnets and radio waves—no intravenous dye required.\n### Key Benefits vs MRI with Contrast\n- \\*\\*Zero contrast dye\\*\\*—ideal for patients with kidney issues or dye allergies\n- \\*\\*Faster appointment slots\\*\\*—no pre-hydration or post-scan observation\n- \\*\\*Lower cost\\*\\*—saves up to 30 % compared with contrast-enhanced studies\n- \\*\\*Same diagnostic accuracy\\*\\* for most common shoulder conditions\n\n## Risks and Limitations of the MRI Shoulder without Contrast\n\n### MRI Safety Considerations\n- \\*\\*No radiation\\*\\*—safe for children and pregnant women (after first trimester)\n- \\*\\*Metal implants\\*\\*—pacemakers, cochlear implants, or older aneurysm clips may be contraindicated\n- \\*\\*Claustrophobia\\*\\*—discuss open-MRI or mild sedation options with Cadabams staff\n### Limitations in Detecting Certain Conditions\n- \\*\\*Small labral fraying\\*\\* may be missed without arthroscopy correlation\n- \\*\\*Active synovitis\\*\\* is better visualised with contrast in rare cases\n- \\*\\*Micro-fractures\\*\\* may require a CT scan for complete evaluation\n\n## Parameters Considered in the MRI Shoulder Without Contrast Scan\n\n- \\*\\*Rotator Cuff Tendons\\*\\*—supraspinatus, infraspinatus, teres minor, subscapularis\n- \\*\\*Labrum & Ligaments\\*\\*—anterior, posterior, and superior labrum; glenohumeral ligaments\n- \\*\\*Bones & Cartilage\\*\\*—humeral head, glenoid, acromion, articular cartilage thickness\n- \\*\\*Fluid Collections\\*\\*—joint effusion, bursal fluid, ganglion cysts\n\n## When to Take Test\n\n\\*\\*Diagnosing Rotator Cuff Tear\\*\\*\nHigh-resolution T2 images reveal tendon discontinuity, retraction, and muscle atrophy.\n\\*\\*Evaluating Shoulder Impingement\\*\\*\nMeasures acromial shape, subacromial space, and bursal thickening.\n\\*\\*Investigating Persistent Shoulder Pain\\*\\*\nRules out occult fractures, cartilage lesions, or early avascular necrosis.\n\n## Benefits of Taking the Test\n\n- \\*\\*High-resolution imaging without radiation\\*\\*—safe for repeated follow-ups\n- \\*\\*Same-day appointment & fast reports\\*\\*—book online, walk out with digital films in 24 hours\n- \\*\\*Cost-effective at Cadabams Diagnostics\\*\\*—packages start at ₹3,500; insurance cashless approved\n\n## Illnesses Diagnosed with MRI Shoulder Without Contrast.\n\n- \\*\\*Rotator Cuff Tear\\*\\*—partial or full-thickness\n- \\*\\*Labral Tears\\*\\*—Bankart, SLAP, posterior\n- \\*\\*Bursitis & Tendinitis\\*\\*—subacromial or subdeltoid bursitis, calcific tendinitis\n- \\*\\*Frozen Shoulder\\*\\*—capsular thickening and restricted joint volume\n\n## Preparing for the Test\n\n### Pre-requisites\n- Remove all metallic jewellery, watches, and hairpins\n- Inform staff of any implants, tattoos, or pregnancy\n- Wear loose cotton clothing or change into Cadabams gown\n### Best Time to Take the Test\nMorning slots reduce waiting time and allow same-day report collection.\n### Eligibility\n- Adults and children > 5 years\n- No fasting required\n- Kidney-function tests not needed (no contrast)\n### Procedure for Taking a MRI Shoulder Without Contrast\n1. Check-in at reception with doctor’s prescription\n2. Complete safety questionnaire\n3. Lie supine with shoulder in dedicated coil; keep still for 15–20 min\n4. Listen to music or watch calming visuals via in-bore screen\n### Caution Before Taking the Test\n- Notify technologist if you experience claustrophobia—Cadabams offers open-MRI or mild sedation on request"
